Designing with AI tools is easier than ever, but Raphael Shod and the host discuss the "good, the bad, and the ugly" of AI-assisted design
. Raphael, co-founder of Cron (sold to Notion) and a top designer, notes that many startup landing pages now feature "dumb hover effects" and ubiquitous purple gradients
. These trends often make websites look the same, as LLMs are trained on existing "good" examples and replicate them quickly, leading to a loss of originality
.
Review: New.ai
The first site, New.ai, is described as "very purple"
. A major critique is a line that follows the scroll up and down the page; the experts find this distracting rather than helpful, likely implemented only because it was easy to do with an LLM
. However, they praise the hover animations for the feature cards as a tasteful and creative use of AI
. Conversely, the navigation menu is criticized because hovering makes items disappear or fade out, which violates standard browser behavior and reduces usability
. Raphael suggests that hover should ideally reveal functionality or make the UI feel alive, but hiding critical info behind it is an anti-pattern
.
Review: Rosebud AI
Rosebud AI also uses the common purple gradient and pinkish accents, making it feel less original
. The site features an interactive browser game, though the reviewers are unsure if it is actual product code or a sandbox
. They suggest the navigation is confusing and that the color combination (red logo on purple) is not complimentary
. A key takeaway is that an H1 headline must clearly state what the product is, who it is for, and why they should care
.
Review: Get Crux
Get Crux is criticized for "scroll jacking" and a button that "chases" the user around the screen, which is viewed as distracting rather than engaging
. The hero image is noted as blurry, and the site suffers from a lack of visual consistency
. Raphael points out that fade-in animations can be problematic if they are on a timer, potentially causing users to scroll past content before it even appears
.
Review: Sphinx
Sphinx is cited for having a confusing information hierarchy with too many text styles
. The experts describe some elements as "LLM hallucinations," such as buttons that move and shift styles every time they are clicked
. The site uses scroll jacking to force an animation that distracts from the actual value proposition
. Raphael emphasizes that the scroll indicator is an important tool for user orientation, and this site fails to provide that clarity
.
Review: Build Zero
Build Zero features distracting vertical movement in its menu and hover effects that cause the menu to shift horizontally, which looks like a bug
. The "fake dashboard" shown on the site uses standard "Google colors" (red, yellow, green, blue), which is a classic hallmark of AI-generated design
. Raphael notes that while "bento boxes" are a popular pattern, they are becoming non-original
. He warns against "AI slop," which occurs when builders outsource their thinking to LLMs
.
Review: Zarna AI
Zarna AI is described as feeling like "molasses" due to heavy scroll jacking and a lack of useful information
. The site uses a dynamic video background that makes the navigation menu unreadable
. While the grainy, zoomed-in visual style is called "fresh," the site lacks meaty content and clear messaging
.
Final Takeaways
Raphael’s main takeaway is that while AI superpowers are wonderful, founders must not outsource their thinking to LLMs
. A landing page is a customer acquisition channel, not just a "cool thing on the web"
. Founders must QA everything for bugs or confusing interactions and be intentional about their brand and color palette rather than just accepting whatever the AI "spits out"